Beryl	An ancient maritime city on the northern coast of the southern continent, situated within a coastal gulf on the Sea of Torments, east of the Strait of Vermust. The oldest of the Jewel Cities and known as their "Queen," Beryl traces its origins back many centuries; its history was described by Croaker as "a bottomless well filled with murky water." Governed for generations by rulers called Syndics, the city speaks the Jewel Cities dialect — a language that served as the spoken tongue of the Black Company for many years and the written form of their Annals. Among its notable landmarks are the Bastion (which contains the Paper Tower), Necropolitan Hill, the Pillar of Anguish, the Fortress Island, the Avenue of the Older Empire, the Avenue of the Syndics, and the impoverished district known as the Groan. Beryl's antiquity, its maritime position on the Sea of Torments, and its long violent history give it a brooding, layered character all its own.
Charm|Tower at Charm	The fortress that serves as both the administrative capital of the Lady's Empire and her personal palace, located in the northern continent. By far the largest structure in the north, it is a featureless black cube of immense scale, built from massive imported basalt billets. The remaining basalt was strewn outward in every direction save a single perfectly manicured approach, restricting all land access to a tightly controlled point; some of these boulders can be animated as grotesque, gargantuan giants to trample attackers. The Tower is manned by the Lady's functionaries and the Tower Guard, a dedicated army hundreds strong. It encloses an inner Tower occupying one-third of its volume, accessible through a single entrance, where visitors are subjected to the Lady's Eye. The Tower also serves as the customary demarcation between east and west across the entire Empire. To the north lie towns such as Elm, Rye, Wist, and Jane, then the Salient and Forsberg beyond; to the south, a few weeks' ride brings one to the coastal Jewel City of Opal and the Sea of Torments. The Stair of Tear lies close by to the east or northeast.
Cho'n Delor	A haunted ruin on the hills beyond the east bank of the great river of the southern continent, above the Second Cataract. Willow Swan likened its silhouette to "a heap of old skulls" overlooking the water. Two hundred years before Croaker's time, Cho'n Delor was a significant regional power, ruled by a brutal tyrant called the Paingod, who hired the Black Company of generations past to fight against the nearby Triplet Cities in the bloody Pastel Wars. Both Cho'n Delor and all three of the Triplet Cities were ultimately destroyed by combat and mighty sorcery in those wars. The ruins have been haunted ever since: no villages have been built near them and even animals keep away. The only nearby settlement is Idon, a walled city of unusual shape — one street wide and of extraordinary length — on the opposite bank, whose inhabitants live in perpetual fear of the ruins and many of whom abandon it for new homes elsewhere as soon as they are able.
Forsberg	The northernmost province of the Lady's Empire in the northern continent, Forsberg was its own independent kingdom before the Lady's consolidation wars. The province's capital and largest city is Oar, located in its northernmost reaches; the next most important site is Deal, a major fortress south of Oar. The native language is Forsberger. Forsberg borders the vast Great Forest to the north and the province of the Salient to the south. It became a hotbed of Rebel activity in the war against the Lady's Empire, with the general Raker driving significant Imperial losses there.
Khatovar	A city of Kina cult-worshipers, and the place of origin of the Free Companies of Khatovar—most prominently the Black Company itself—which were created there and sent across the glittering plain into the homeworld and other worlds. Their mission was to find the best location for a sacred religious rite called the Year of the Skulls. Over the centuries that followed, the meaning and nature of Khatovar were entirely lost to later generations of Black Company soldiers. After the Battle of the Barrowland, Croaker vowed to return the Company's Annals to this mysterious origin, setting the course for the Company's long southward odyssey. The name carries translations in different sources: "Khadi's Throne", "Place from which Khadi went forth", or simply "Khadi's gate."
Lords	A major city in the Lady's Empire in the northern continent, situated east of the Forest of Cloud, north of the Windy Country, and west of the Plain of Fear. A long road skirting the southern edge of the Forest of Cloud connects it to the Salient province to the west. The city was placed under the authority of Nightcrawler, one of the Ten Who Were Taken. When the Black Company captured Whisper's hidden base camp in the Forest of Cloud, they seized detailed battle plans for a Rebel uprising within Lords — a scheme to embed fighters secretly among Rebel sympathizers and strike Nightcrawler's garrison from within. Forewarned, Nightcrawler struck swiftly and hanged the embedded Rebels from the city's trees and lampposts. The Black Company subsequently quartered in Lords, expecting a quiet winter, before being drawn into renewed fighting. It was here that Soulcatcher revealed to Company senior members that the Limper had been secretly suborned by Whisper, who had learned his True Name. Lords was later besieged by Harden and other Circle members, forcing roughly three thousand Imperial troops and Company soldiers to abandon the city and flee into the Windy Country.
Plain of Fear	A bizarre desert in the eastern portion of the northern continent, the Plain of Fear is home to over forty unique and intelligent species found nowhere else: windwhales, flying mantas, reversed centaurs, talking buzzards, and enigmatic talking stones called menhirs, among others. The Plain is also notorious for supernatural "change storms" that can transform any living thing caught in them. At its heart resides Father Tree, an alien entity worshiped by the Plain's creatures and the rare wild human tribes as their god, who serves as its ultimate protector and ruler.
Roses	A major walled city in the central part of the Lady's Empire, enclaved within the Salient province. Despite lying within firmly Imperial territory, Roses holds the unique distinction of being a free republic with its own independent sovereignty. Its walls are painted pale red, three rivers course through it connected by a web of canals, and its numerous arched bridges are among the city's most celebrated features. The Rosean language originated here. A road to the south connects Roses to Meystrikt, the most important fortress of the Salient.
Rust	One of five huge and formidable cities forming an arc east of the Plain of Fear in the northern continent, alongside Frost, Thud, Ade, and Barns. Rust was the focus of numerous protracted and bloody Rebel uprisings against the Lady's Empire. The fighting around Rust was described as particularly bitter and sustained, with both sides driven to extreme measures during prolonged sieges. The city was also notable for its "amazon regiments": Rebel formations composed entirely of women.
Rye	A noteworthy town or city in the northern portion of the Lady's Empire, besieged by the Rebel. Its precise location is not fully given in the Annals, though context places it south of the Salient and west of Lords, in a region associated with Elm, Wist, Jane, and Wine. One of the most effective of the Ten Who Were Taken, Shapeshifter, was dispatched there to hold the city against the Rebel siege.
Salient	A long, arrowhead-shaped province of flatland pointing south between mountain ranges in the northern continent. Its most important city is Roses, a free republican enclave, and its most important fortress is Meystrikt. Forsberg lies to the north, the Forest of Cloud to the east, and a long road links the Salient to the major city of Lords. Presumed one of the earliest provinces absorbed into the Lady's Empire, given its proximity to the Tower at Charm.
Stair of Tear	A mountain range of sandstone bluffs, pillars, and mesas in the northern continent, named after its single steep pass: an old road that climbs steeply through countless switchbacks, resembling from a distance a giant's lopsided stairway. The Windy Country lies immediately to its north, and the Tower at Charm, the capital of the Lady's Empire, lies not far to the south.
Were	A city or town in the eastern reaches of the Lady's Empire in the northern continent, mentioned once in the Annals by Soulcatcher. Site of a notable battle between Soulcatcher, the most powerful of the Ten Who Were Taken, and Whisper, the most dangerous Rebel leader of the Circle of Eighteen. Soulcatcher cited Were alongside Rust and the Plain of Fear as locations where she had faced Whisper directly.
Windy Country	An inhospitable desert in the northern continent, lying west of the Plain of Fear and east of the Forest of Cloud and the city of Lords. Described as a "big emptiness where the wind blows all the time", it contains no regular fixed tracks and was shunned by the Lady's Empire as worthless wasteland. The Black Company was forced to trek through it after abandoning Lords to the Rebel, pursued by Harden and members of the Circle of Eighteen; Stormbringer exacerbated the already punishing conditions with a massive, unrelenting storm aimed directly at the pursuing forces. The Company and its Imperial allies endured the crossing and ultimately reached the Stair of Tear. The Windy Country's deep canyons also later served as daytime refuge for covert Company teams evading detection from above.
